citeinfo.title: Accessible Recreation Destinations

descript.abstract: Accessible recreation sites throughout New York State that are owned, maintained or jointly managed by DEC
descript.purpose: For public awareness of recreational opportunities that are accessible to people with disabilities.
descript.supplinf: We encourage visitors to contact DEC's Access Coordinators directly ( http://www.dec.ny.gov/outdoor/42324.html ) to discuss their individual needs and recreational pursuits with knowledgeable staff. Many of DEC's accessible recreation sites were designed to provide people with choices about the type of recreational experience and level of personal challenge they prefer. Outdoor facilities are susceptible to storm damage, weathering and natural disturbance.

theme.themekey: recreational opportunities for people with disabilities

The user must be aware of data conditions and bear responsibility for the appropriate use of the information with respect to possible errors, original map scale, collection methodology, currency of data, and other conditions.

attracc.attraccr: All attributes were manually entered, based on staff inspections. Sites were inspected by DEC staff, trained in the ADAAG Proposed Guidelines for Outdoor Recreation Areas (United States Access Board, 2007). Not all features at each site meet these guidelines, however features that do meet the guidelines are marked Y in the attribute tables.

dataqual.logic: While most points represent a single accessible site, a few represent a destination grouping of nearby and related accessible facilities.
dataqual.complete: Based on staff inspections, sites without any features meeting proposed ADAAG for Outdoor Areas or that do not provide meaningful access to recreation were omitted. http://www.access-board.gov/recreation/guides/index.htm

horizpa.horizpar: Points are generally located at a site's parking area or entrance (larger facilities). A few points are used to represent access to a larger area (ex. Moose River Plains, one point at the beginning of the road with numerous accessible campsites spread out along the length of the road)

srcinfo.srccontr: GPS locations recorded for some sites, especially DEC Region 6
Locations of sites based on directions and descriptions given by DEC staff
Site locations based on satellite photo, DEC Land boundaries, waterbody location and road locations.

procstep.procdesc: The data layer was created by plotting points over a backdrop of Orthoimagery and ALIS roads datasets to correspond with known, completed and inspected accessible recreation projects and sites. The data was gradually expanded as more sites were brought to the attention of staff in the DEC's Division of Lands & Forests, Universal Access Program at 518-402-9428. The data will be updated periodically as new sites are completed, renovated or brought to our attention.
